      howMeasured:
        '<p>Persons are to be regarded as forming a single household if</p><p>(a) they are all members of the same family, or</p><p>(b) their circumstances are those specified in <a target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer nofollow" href="https://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2006/373/regulation/3">this legislation</a> or <a target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer nofollow" href="https://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2006/373/regulation/4">this legislation</a><br><br>For the purposes of the above a person is a member of the same family as another person ifâ</p><ul><li><p>those persons are married to, or civil partners of, each other or live together as if they were a married couple or civil partners;</p></li><li><p>one of them is a relative of the other; or</p></li><li><p>one of them is, or is a relative of, one member of a couple and the other is a relative of the other member of the couple.</p></li></ul><p>For those purposes</p><ul><li><p>a âcoupleâ means two persons who are married to, or civil partners of, each other or live together as if they were a married couple or civil partners;</p></li><li><p>ârelativeâ means parent, grandparent, child, grandchild, brother, sister, uncle, aunt, nephew, niece or cousin;</p></li><li><p>a relationship of the half-blood shall be treated as a relationship of the whole blood; and</p></li><li><p>the stepchild of a person shall be treated as his child.</p></li></ul>',
